---
// /dev/m18-train/ -- internal-only smoke page for M18 Slice 3.
//
// NOT linked from nav. Runs the full 2,000-iter training in-browser and shows
// the live loss curve next to the nanoGPT reference trajectory + a ±0.1 nat
// envelope. The page is the convergence gate per docs/plans/2026-04-29-m18-
// capstone-implementation.md §4.5.

export const prerender = false;
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import M18TrainSmoke from '../../components/demos/M18TrainSmoke.svelte';
---

<Base title="M18 Train Smoke" prose>
  <article class="dev-page">
    <header>
      <p class="kicker">/dev · M18 Slice 3</p>
      <h1>Train smoke test</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        The M18 convergence gate. Press start: the WGSL engine runs 2,000 iters
        of training on tiny-shakespeare-char in this tab, with the live loss
        curve overlaid against the nanoGPT reference oracle. The badge passes
        when every 100-iter checkpoint sits inside the ±0.1-nat envelope.
      </p>
    </header>

    <M18TrainSmoke client:only="svelte" />

    <section class="notes">
      <h2>What this checks</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Preflight gradient check.</strong> One element per layer-type is perturbed by ε=1e-3; the finite-difference (L(θ+ε) − L(θ−ε))/2ε is compared to the analytical gradient produced by the backward pass. Catches a backward kernel that the per-kernel CPU twins missed.</li>
        <li><strong>Convergence gate.</strong> The WGSL engine's <code>train_nll</code> (EWMA decay 0.9) and <code>val_nll</code> (mean over 20 batches) must lie within ±0.1 nat of the reference at iters 0, 100, 200, …, 1900, 1999. The reference was generated by <code>scripts/m18/nanogpt_reference.py</code> with seed 1337.</li>
        <li><strong>Run config.</strong> <code>n_layer=4, n_head=4, d_model=64, d_ff=256, T=64, vocab=65</code>, AdamW <code>(β₁=0.9, β₂=0.95, ε=1e-8, λ=0.1)</code>, grad-clip 1.0, cosine-decay LR from 3e-4 (after a 100-iter linear warmup) to 3e-5 over 2,000 steps, batch 32.</li>
        <li><strong>If the gate fails despite preflight + per-kernel CPU twins passing.</strong> Stop. Do <em>not</em> silently switch to webgpu-torch. The point of this slice is to expose whether the WGSL stack is real.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .dev-page {
    max-width: 760px;
    margin: 3rem auto;
    padding: 0 1.25rem;
    display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2rem;
  }
  header { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.65rem; }
  .kicker {
    margin: 0; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.78rem;
    text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: var(--site-fg-muted);
  }
  h1 { margin: 0; font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: clamp(1.7rem, 3vw, 2.2rem); font-weight: 700; }
  .lede { margin: 0; color: var(--site-fg-muted); line-height: 1.6; }

  .notes h2 {
    margin: 0 0 0.55rem; font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
  }
  .notes ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; line-height: 1.65; color: var(--site-fg); }
  .notes li { margin-bottom: 0.6rem; }
  .notes code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.85em;
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--site-fg) 6%, transparent);
    padding: 0.05rem 0.35rem; border-radius: 4px;
  }
</style>
